ing capabilities, as is everyone, but if they will only navigate shallows at high speeds then that dog don't hunt.  Seems like a good way to get killed!  Are there ANY guides on the White using jet Jons or semi-V's??  Sure would be nice to get rid of the prop if it is reasonable to do so.<br>
<br>
Since I've never been on the White I'm ignorrant about it except for what I've read here and on other web sites.  Is there a permanent channel that remains navigable even at low water times?  We're going to be living 6 minutes from Beaver Dam starting this summer.<br>
<br>
Jimmy pointed out that throwing up a wake is not only bad manners, but also a violation within 100 ft of an anchored boat.  What ever I buy must be able to navigate at the appropriate speed in traffic areas on the river during low water.    <br>
<br>
The Merc Sport Jet 175 2 stroke has to be the pits on gas since it has two things going against it; jet &amp; 2 stroke.  But, gas is cheap in the scheme of things.  Sure, it would be nice to run a quiet and more fuel efficient 4 stroke, but who wants a 500 lb V-8 engine weighing things down?  That brings me to 4 stroke outboards!!  Sounds like the best of both worlds to me.  Anyone have experience with them?  <br>
<br>
Regards,<br>
<br>
John Dent <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F9FBFD><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bflyfishingarkansasandmissouri.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jimmyt@flyfishingarkansasandmissouri>Jimmy T</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 59<br> <font color=#000000>(4/25/03 5:42 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=68.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Welcome Abord </span><hr size=1> Welcome Abord John.<br>
