<br>
I understand that you practically live on the White and that is amazing.  The fact that you, as an expert guide and river boatsman, have had your share of bad luck and destroyed so many outboard engines I wonder what kind of luck newbie rookies could expect on the White.  I'm not going to get serious about boats until I'm up there and see what everyone else is driving, but you sure make a good argument for a jet boat.  Eliminating the protrusions below the keel and getting rid of the propellor just seems like a good idea considering the odds of hitting things that don't &quot;give&quot;.  <br>
<br>
Best Regards,<br>
<br>
JD <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F9FBFD><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bflyfishingarkansasandmissouri.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jimmyt@flyfishingarkansasandmissouri>Jimmy T</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 62<br> <font color=#000000>(4/28/03 4:24 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fflyfishingarkansasandmissourifrm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=68.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Experts</span><hr size=1> Hey JD,<br>
<br>
I don't claim to be an expert at anything.  It's an interesting word given to marksman of course.  I see EXPERTS on tv picking stocks and they get it wrong a lot so I wouldn't consider them experts.<br>
<br>
A couple of reasons for staying in front of the water are:<br>
1)  Some flyfishers simply don't like to fish out of the boat.<br>
2) With absolute beginers it's much easier to instruct standing on firm ground rather than from a boat and a heck of a lot safer as well<br>
3) Sometimes the water is so darn trashey (mossey) that you really don't have a choice if you want to catch fish.<br>
<br>
As for riding the rise.  As the water comes up the fish really turn on and bite like the dickens.  They'll eat just about anything.  If there were a kitchen sink fly I'd bet a $100 they would strike it and you would catch fish.  <br>
<br>
JD see other post as to why few guides use jet motors.<br>
<br>
It's also a good argument as to why not to use a jet JD.<br>
Try to make an S turn in low water going up or down stream in a jet and you will soon switch.   <br>
<br>
Good luck in your move to our beautiful state.  You will like the low taxes, scenery, lack of smog,little if no traffic,few red lights and especially the fishing.<br>
<br>
Jimmy T<br>
